---
import TopNav from "../components/TopNav.astro";

const freeStateLogoUrl = organizationAssetUrl("freestateprojectlogo.png");

function organizationAssetUrl(filename = "") {
  return `/api/organization-assets/${String(filename)
    .split("/")
    .map((part) => encodeURIComponent(part))
    .join("/")}`;
}
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="/NH%20DB%20Logo.png" />
    <link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/NH%20DB%20Logo.png" />
    <title>What Are Free Staters? | NH Deserves Better</title>
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="Learn what the Free State Project is, why it is controversial, and why it matters in New Hampshire politics."
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <TopNav />
    <main class="page">
      <a class="back" href="/">Back home</a>

      <section class="hero">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <p class="eyebrow">Civic Glossary</p>
          <h1>What Are Free Staters?</h1>
          <p class="lede">
            The Free State Project is a political movement founded in 2001 with
            the goal of encouraging thousands of libertarian-minded people to move
            to New Hampshire and reshape state government.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-logo">
          <img src={freeStateLogoUrl} alt="Free State Project logo" />
        </div>
      </section>

      <article class="content-panel">
        <section>
          <h2>The Movement</h2>
          <p>
            Rather than building a national movement, the project's strategy is
            to concentrate supporters in one state where they can have greater
            influence over elections, legislation, and public policy.
          </p>
          <p>
            Today, many of the movement's participants serve in the New
            Hampshire Legislature, local government, and advocacy organizations,
            making it one of the state's most organized political forces.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Why Are Free Staters Controversial?</h2>
          <p>
            Critics argue that the movement has had an outsized influence on New
            Hampshire politics and is working to fundamentally change the role
            of government in the state. They point to efforts to:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Cut funding for public education while expanding school voucher programs</li>
            <li>Reduce business and other state taxes, shifting more of the burden onto local property taxpayers</li>
            <li>Roll back environmental regulations and public health protections</li>
            <li>Reduce funding for healthcare and other public services</li>
            <li>Override local control on issues like housing and zoning</li>
            <li>Advance legislation targeting LGBTQ+ rights, particularly transgender people</li>
            <li>Shrink state government by reducing agencies, programs, and regulations</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            Critics also argue that highly organized Free State activists have
            helped shift legislative priorities away from issues like affordable
            housing, healthcare costs, workforce shortages, and public
            education, toward ideological and culture-war legislation.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="callout">
          <h2>Supporters Say...</h2>
          <p>
            Supporters of the Free State Project argue they are simply
            exercising their right to participate in democracy. They believe
            lower taxes, smaller government, fewer regulations, and greater
            individual freedom make New Hampshire a better place to live and do
            business.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Why It Matters</h2>
          <p>
            Whether you support or oppose the Free State Project, its influence
            on New Hampshire politics is significant. Understanding which
            elected officials are aligned with the movement can help voters
            better understand the priorities and policies shaping the state's
            future.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="source-note">
          <h2>How We Use This Designation</h2>
          <p>
            On NH Deserves Better, Free Stater designations are based on
            candidate endorsements published by the
            <a href="https://www.nhliberty.org/home/2024-2025-biennium-candidate-endorsements-and-results/">
              New Hampshire Liberty Alliance
            </a>.
            The NH Liberty Alliance describes those endorsements as applying to
            2024 New Hampshire State Representative and State Senator candidates,
            with endorsements for current legislators based on Liberty Ratings
            scores and new candidate endorsements based on its candidate survey.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>

<style>
  :global(body) {
    margin: 0;
    font-family:
      Inter, ui-sans-serif, system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI",
      sans-serif;
    background: #f7f4ee;
    color: #1f2933;
  }

  .page {
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 40px 0 80px;
    width: min(960px, calc(100% - 32px));
  }

  .back,
  a {
    color: #1f2933;
    font-weight: 800;
  }

  .hero {
    align-items: center;
    display: grid;
    gap: 28px;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(180px, 260px);
    padding: 40px 0 28px;
  }

  .hero-logo {
    align-items: center;
    background: white;
    border: 2px solid #1f2933;
    border-radius: 12px;
    box-shadow: 5px 5px 0 #1f2933;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: 24px;
  }

  .hero-logo img {
    display: block;
    height: auto;
    max-height: 180px;
    object-fit: contain;
    width: 100%;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    color: #6b4f2a;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 900;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    margin: 0 0 12px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(3rem, 8vw, 6rem);
    line-height: 0.95;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .lede {
    color: #374151;
    font-size: clamp(1.2rem, 2.4vw, 1.55rem);
    font-weight: 750;
    line-height: 1.45;
    margin: 24px 0 0;
    max-width: 820px;
  }

  .content-panel {
    background: white;
    border: 2px solid #1f2933;
    border-radius: 12px;
    box-shadow: 6px 6px 0 #1f2933;
    display: grid;
    gap: 28px;
    padding: clamp(22px, 4vw, 40px);
  }

  section + section {
    border-top: 1px solid #d1d5db;
    padding-top: 28px;
  }

  h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.15rem);
    line-height: 1.05;
    margin: 0 0 14px;
  }

  p,
  li {
    color: #374151;
    font-size: 1.04rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  p {
    margin: 0;
  }

  p + p,
  ul + p {
    margin-top: 16px;
  }

  ul {
    display: grid;
    gap: 10px;
    margin: 18px 0 0;
    padding-left: 22px;
  }

  li {
    padding-left: 4px;
  }

  .callout {
    background: #fffaf1;
    border: 1px solid #d1d5db;
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 22px;
  }

  .callout + section {
    border-top: 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .hero {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .hero-logo {
      justify-self: start;
      max-width: 220px;
      padding: 18px;
    }

    .content-panel {
      box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #1f2933;
    }
  }
</style>
